cs.DL, cs.CY, cs.IR, cs.CR, cs.SI 

The paper analyzes the research performance of university researchers in the hard sciences, which includes computer science. The use of bibliometric methodology suggests a focus on quantitative analysis, which is common in the sub-categories of cs.DL (Digital Libraries) and cs.IR (Information Retrieval). The analysis of performance differences among academic ranks may also relate to issues of academic career advancement, which could be relevant to the sub-category of cs.CY (Computers and Society). The study of productivity in specific disciplines could be relevant to sub-categories such as cs.CR (Cryptography and Security) and cs.SI (Social and Information Networks).
